      "term": "Generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "The process of converting energy sources like gas, wind, or nuclear into electrical energy.",
      "anchor": "The starting point of the electrical supply chain.",
      "misconception": "Believing electricity is created from nothing rather than converted from another energy source."
    },
    {
      "term": "Transmission",
      "simpleDefinition": "The bulk movement of electricity over long distances at very high voltages.",
      "anchor": "The 'motorway' system of the electrical grid.",
      "misconception": "Confusing transmission (long-distance high voltage) with distribution (local lower voltage)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Micro-generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "Small-scale production of electricity, usually at the point of use like solar panels on a house.",
      "anchor": "Local power for local needs.",
      "misconception": "Thinking micro-generation is the same as large-scale power station generation."
    },
    {
      "term": "Transmission Voltages",
      "simpleDefinition": "The specific high voltages used in the UK grid: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV.",
      "anchor": "400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV.",
      "misconception": "Thinking electricity is transmitted at the same 230V used in domestic sockets."
    },
    {
      "term": "Step-up Transformer",
      "simpleDefinition": "A device used at power stations to increase voltage for efficient transmission.",
      "anchor": "Boosting voltage to reduce energy loss.",
      "misconception": "Believing that increasing the voltage also increases the total amount of power available."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV are the UK transmission voltages.",
    "High voltage is used to reduce energy loss over long distances.",
    "Micro-generation happens at the point of use.",
    "The National Grid connects generation to the consumer."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Electricity is generated at 230V.",
    "Transmission and distribution are the same thing.",
    "Voltage is increased to create more energy."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "The National Grid Overview",
      "objective": "Define the role of centralized generation in the UK electrical supply system.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Electricity generation is the starting point of the electrical supply chain. It is the process of converting energy sources, such as gas or wind, into electrical energy. In the UK, this happens at large power stations located across the country. These stations do not send electricity directly to your home at a low voltage; instead, they feed into a massive interconnected network called the National Grid.",
        "The National Grid acts like a motorway system for electricity, connecting the large-scale generators to the areas where the power is needed. This centralized system ensures that if one power station is turned off for maintenance, electricity can be diverted from another part of the country. This transition from the power station to the high-voltage network is the first step in getting power from the source to the consumer."
      ],
      "hint": "Think of the National Grid as the 'motorway' that connects the power station to the rest of the country."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "UK Transmission Voltages",
      "objective": "Identify the standard high voltages used for transmission in the UK grid.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Once electricity is generated, it must be moved over long distances. This stage is called transmission. To do this efficiently, the voltage is increased to very high levels. In the UK, there are three specific standard transmission voltages you must recognize: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV.",
        "The abbreviation 'kV' stands for kilovolt. Since 'kilo' means one thousand, 400 kV is actually 400,000 volts. These extremely high voltages are used exclusively for the bulk movement of electricity across the country using pylons and heavy-duty cables. These voltages are much higher than the 230V (volts) used in domestic sockets or the 400V used in three-phase commercial supplies. You must remember these three specific values—400, 275, and 132—as they define the UK transmission network."
      ],
      "hint": "The three voltages are 400, 275, and 132. Remember that kV stands for kilovolts."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-3",
      "title": "Large-Scale Generation Methods",
      "objective": "Identify the main large-scale generation methods used to supply the grid.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Large-scale generation involves using different energy sources to spin a turbine, which then drives a generator to produce electricity. These sources are categorized into fossil fuels, nuclear, and renewables. Fossil fuel methods include burning coal, oil, or gas. Biomass is another thermal method where organic materials are burned to create steam.",
        "Renewable methods harness natural forces. Wind generation uses large turbines, while hydro (hydroelectric) uses the flow of water from dams. Wave energy captures the movement of the ocean. Nuclear power uses atomic reactions to create the heat required for steam turbines. All these methods are designed to produce massive amounts of power constantly to meet the high demand of the national population. Each method converts a primary energy source into the electrical energy that enters the transmission grid."
      ],
      "hint": "Large-scale methods include coal, gas, nuclear, wind, hydro, and biomass."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-4",
      "title": "Micro-Generation and Local Supply",
      "objective": "Explain what micro-generation is and how it differs from large-scale generation.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "While large-scale generation happens at massive power stations, micro-generation is the small-scale production of electricity. The key difference is that micro-generation happens at the 'point of use.' This means the electricity is generated exactly where it is going to be consumed, such as on the roof of a house or a small business premises.",
        "The most common form of micro-generation is Photovoltaic (PV) systems, often simply called solar panels. These convert sunlight directly into electricity. Because the power is generated locally, it does not have to travel through miles of transmission cables to reach the user. This reduces the demand on the National Grid and minimizes the energy lost during transport. Other forms can include small-scale wind turbines or micro-hydro systems, but they all share the same goal: local power for local needs."
      ],
      "hint": "Micro-generation happens at the 'point of use,' like solar panels (PV) on a house."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-5",
      "title": "Why Transmission Uses High Voltage",
      "objective": "Explain why electricity is transmitted at very high voltage over long distances.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Electricity is transmitted at very high voltages (400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV) to solve a physical problem: energy loss. When electricity flows through a cable, the cable has a natural resistance. This resistance causes some of the electrical energy to turn into heat, which is wasted. The amount of heat lost is directly related to the amount of current (measured in Amps) flowing through the wire.",
        "To reduce this loss, engineers use a 'Step-up Transformer' at the power station. This device increases the voltage significantly. Because of the way electrical power works, increasing the voltage allows us to decrease the current while still delivering the same amount of total power. Because the current is now much lower, the cables stay cooler and very little energy is lost as heat during the journey across the country. This makes long-distance transmission efficient and cost-effective."
      ],
      "hint": "High voltage allows for lower current, which means less energy is lost as heat in the cables."
    }
  ]
}

